        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:100:"How bad does depression suck? Panel recommends screening every adult whether acting like one or not.";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:130:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2016/01/depression-screening-recommended-for-every-adult-whether-actin-like-one-or-not/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:139:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2016/01/depression-screening-recommended-for-every-adult-whether-actin-like-one-or-not/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 26 Jan 2016 23:08:31 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/?p=3852";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15369:"<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-1.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-3903" alt="Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-1" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-1-162x300.jpg" width="162" height="300" /></a>Dear Mr. Happy-Go-Lucky,

Honestly, I didn't mean to eavesdrop as we were both vacuuming our cars today at the same service station, but I couldn't help overhearing you "encouraging" your special So &amp; So to get out of her slump and put air in the tires.

"Is it really that bad?" you hollered through the windshield, laughing. "I mean, seriously, come on. You've gotta shake this off!" When you draped the hose of the vacuum around your neck, Britney-Boa-Style, I chuckled.

But when she leaned her head against the passenger window, the heel of one hand pressed hard against her brow and the back of the other hand across her mouth, I recognized her silent struggle.

This got me thinking, in a less-than-happy-go-lucky way, how you weren't helping her at all, just shaming her into being happy like you.

And while I really don't know your special So &amp; So -- or how you got to be so Happy-Go-Lucky-ish, it seems to me she was <em>really</em> down -- and that you were really, truly, assertively <em>not</em>.

You see, I'm grateful that your So &amp; So's body language revealed her feelings, because depression presents in many ways: withdrawal; substance abuse, anger, self-harm. You seemed blissfully unaware of the brief eye contact I made with her, our wordless exchange translating to this:

Me: "You okay?"
So &amp; So: "Not really. This absolutely sucks. I can barely move."
Me: "Been there. I get it."
So &amp; So: "Any ideas on how to push <em>through it?</em>."
Me: [Tilting my head toward you with a gassy smile]
So &amp; So: [Dramatic eye-roll, implying I take both you and your…little hose]

[caption id="attachment_3883" align="alignleft" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-9.24.00-PM.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-3883" alt="Photo: avidly.org" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-9.24.00-PM-300x223.png" width="300" height="223" /></a> Photo: avidly.org[/caption]

Listen, Mr. Happy-Go-Lucky. It's clear that you're fully aware of what a positive attitude looks like to others, all happy and balanced and optimistic about the future. Believe me: I saw that positive attitude admiring itself in the shine of your Kia Sorento. And no, that wasn't sarcastic. The Sorento's a surprisingly cute car, and that tagline? "The Perfect Getaway Vehichle" -- it really suits you, Man. I don't know why. It just does.

But, <a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/11/mother-daughter-dance-with-depression-christine-wolf-teen-adolecent/">as a 47-year-old mother still recovering from a major depressive episode while supporting her teenage daughter through her own struggle with depression</a>, today's <a href="http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=2484345">statement issued by the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, which recommends screening every adult (18 and older) for depression</a> -- is more than just exciting, breaking news for people like So &amp; So and me. This news should also matter to you, and to everyone else you care about, especially since <a href="http://www.nami.org/Learn-More/Mental-Health-By-the-Numbers">there's a 1 in 5 chance you'll be touched by mental illness, too</a>.

According to the <a href="http://www.nami.org/Learn-More/Mental-Health-By-the-Numbers">National Alliance on Mental Illness, less than half (41%) of U.S. adults with a mental health condition received treatment by mental health services in the past year</a>, contributing to America's<a href="http://www.nami.org/Learn-More/Mental-Health-By-the-Numbers"> $193.2 billion in lost wages per year</a>. That's almost 8 million Sorentos getting away from Happy-Go-Lucky dudes like you.

And if you <em>still</em> don't care, or think this announcement doesn't affect your happy life, just remember there's a decent chance that at least 1 in 5 of your children's<strong> teachers, coaches, </strong>and<strong> guidance counselors </strong>have experienced, are currently experiencing, or<strong> </strong>will experience mental illness. One in five of your<strong> colleagues </strong>and<strong> supervisors, </strong>your<strong> doctors, dentists, </strong>and<strong> local government officials, </strong>your<strong> adult friends, family members, neighbors, </strong><strong>registered gun owners, unregistered </strong><strong>gun owners, </strong><strong>fellow airline passengers </strong>and<strong> commuter train passengers, </strong><strong>pharmacists, elected officials, clergy, Facebook friends, favorite authors, bloggers, <strong>auto mechanics, electricians, and firefighters. </strong></strong>And, 1 in 5 of the <strong>adult drivers sharing the road with you</strong> has experienced/is currently dealing with/will experience mental illness.

We're gonna get you, sucka. Just try and get away from us.

In fact, I've been one of those drivers sharing the road with you, and there were days over these last three months that you'd be glad you didn't know I was there. Days when I couldn't stop crying, couldn't feel happy, couldn't feel any hope. Days when I was still getting used to a new medication, hadn't slept well, felt consumed by my sadness. Days when I looked around at drivers like you, staring into your rearview mirrors, admiring your Happy-Go-Lucky smiles, oblivious to the traffic jams of my emotions gone awry and the standstill of self-loathing in my heart. These are things you could not see, nor could I see my way around. I'd have days driving near the holocaust museum, bursting into tears as it came into view, or over falling leaves, marking the end of a season.

I really feel for you, Mr. Happy-Go-Lucky, because I can see how depression would confuse you if you haven't experienced it yourself. Maybe So &amp; So feels general malaise all the time, or maybe it's only once in a long while. As a caregiver, you're understandably exhausted -- even exasperated -- by the unrelenting gloom, but how do you think it feels to be in her head?

I totally get why it's hard to support someone suffering through depression, especially if you've never personally experienced scorching, emotional pain. In a way, it must be like watching a car wreck happening and not being able to do a thing. Whether it plays out in slow-mo or in the blink of an eye, there's barely time to react until the crash is upon you (and just for the record, this same rule applies for the person who's depressed).

Perhaps your So &amp; So also sends you inconsistent SOS signals -- "I can't stand myself…and why don't you love me?" "I'm worthless…and you don't appreciate my value." "I'm so lonely…get away I'm unlovable."

I can only guess that helping her sometimes feels like you're bolting from your Sorento, running toward the overturned wreckage of her self-esteem, only to hear her scream at you from the driver's seat, "You? Now? Leave me alone! I don't need you, Mr. Happy-Go-Lucky. I need Jake from State Farm. He won't judge."

[caption id="attachment_3885" align="alignleft" width="270"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-10.33.27-PM.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-3885" alt="Screen Shot 2016-01-26 at 10.33.27 PM" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-10.33.27-PM-270x300.png" width="270" height="300" /></a> Photo: imgarcade.co[/caption]

Depression, unfortunately, isn't a choice. No one welcomes it, and it's nearly impossible just to "shake off". If we could make it stop, we would, but we can't.

Picture your beautiful car as <em>depression</em>, and a fresh, icy blanket of snow <em>distorted thinking</em>. No matter how clean and tuned up you may be, you can't stop the snow from falling down. You see the clear road two feet to your left, but you're trapped -- less by the snow than by the <em>belief</em> you're stuck there forever. Your handy tools seem too cumbersome to bother digging out, and as you keep spinning and spinning and spinning your wheels, you loose traction and fuel and drive yourself downright crazy.

But when some well-meaning crackerjack like you (no offense) stands on the clear pavement doing a bellydance yelling, "Is it really that bad?" you're seriously not helping by stating the obvious.

<em>Perspective</em> is the antidote for <em>distorted thinking</em>, so sprinkle that <del>shit</del> salt all over that icy snow. Melt the stuff down, Dude. Reach into the window, crank that wheel a smidge to the left, then remain on standby while <em>depression</em> works its way out. Don't try to rescue or be the hero, even though God knows you deserve a medal. That will come later, after the melt. But if you can't understand this or can't follow these instructions, head to the nearest 7-Eleven, buy the latest issue of Hot Rod, and let the grownups figure life out.

Okay…my tough love rant is now over.

But you can stop beating yourself up. Depression isn't easy for anyone to understand, let alone manage.

I just want to make sure we both agree that, while a label certainly doesn't define the person, "depression" has a way of feeling like it does, thanks to our own cognitive distortions reinforced by frustration from others:

"I'm <em>Depressed</em>."
"Why am I so <em>Depressed</em>?"
"Why can't I stop being <em>Depressed</em>?"
"You're making me <em>Depressed</em>."
"Why am I the only one who's <em>Depressed</em>?"
"I shouldn't be <em>Depressed</em>."
"I should have realized sooner that I was feeling <em>Depressed</em>."

We "should" and "shouldn't" all over ourselves, to the point of believing we deserve to feel this bad…only to hear our negative thoughts echoed by others:

"She's <em>still</em> Depressed?"
"Will she <em>always</em> be Depressed?"
"Does <em>everyone</em> get that angry when they're Depressed?"
"I can't even <em>remember</em> when she wasn't Depressed."
"<em>How long</em> does it usually take for her to stop being Depressed?"
"<em>Are you serious</em>? You're actually Depressed over <em>that</em>?"

Look. It's not your fault you can't always be there for her in the ways that she needs, because so few of us are comfortable talking about this subject. And yet depression is real, and it's difficult -- for you and for her. Sometimes, the best way to coax her out of that rut or that wreckage  is to stand there, even as the gapers gawk, just showing her you're not grooving for the getaway today.

What depression does best is to test one's sense of trust -- in ourselves, in others, and in everything we know -- so it might take some patience before she presses the "unlock" button. She's not trying to be difficult. That's the worst part about depression. She doesn't want to be locked inside. She wants to be out there, vacuuming with your…little hose…but your Happy-Go-Lucky dance, to her, feels like a mockery. Between us, she's jealous as hell that you're pulling a Britney when she's glued to her seat. She wants to join you and breathe the diesel fumes all around us, but she can't. Just not right now. But she will. So for now, put down your little hose and just park yourself there, with your Happy-Go-Lucky-ness. Sooner or later she'll eventually signal she's ready. Just remember:  your Sorento was redesigned to be "<strong>Sleek</strong> and <strong>Strong</strong> And <strong>Adaptive To Your Needs</strong>," but when someone's depressed, they'll be anything but.

Oh, if you could only see how many of us struggle in silence due to stigma, more comfortable projecting our pride than accepting society's labels: <strong>Depressed</strong>; <strong>Overwhelmed</strong>; <strong>Unbalanced</strong>. These labels <em>are not who we are as individuals</em> -- they're just feelings -- and believe it or not, we already know that. But while logic tells us feelings are not always the truth, try explaining that to someone whose wife left him for another, or to the mother whose child has died of cancer, or to the young man who just lost his third job, or to the woman who cannot conceive, or to the man who numbs his pain with alcohol, or to the middle-aged mother who's lost her sense of self. These feelings of sadness and desperation are <em><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>real</strong></span></em>, and they're sneaky little buggers, like Smart Cars in your blind spot.

But I really don't want to trouble you, Mr. HGL, and I've taken up far too much time. I can only imagine how this subject matter's probably blown one of your gaskets. I just had to write to let you know how much I recognized your efforts to cheer your So &amp; So up, and that next time, the best thing you can do, if I may be so bold, is to consider depression for what it is: a journey best navigated through compassionate merging, rather than forcing someone into the fast lane.

