Perhaps your So &amp; So also sends you inconsistent SOS signals -- "I can't stand myself…and why don't you love me?" "I'm worthless…and you don't appreciate my value." "I'm so lonely…get away I'm unlovable."

I can only guess that helping her sometimes feels like you're bolting from your Sorento, running toward the overturned wreckage of her self-esteem, only to hear her scream at you from the driver's seat, "You? Now? Leave me alone! I don't need you, Mr. Happy-Go-Lucky. I need Jake from State Farm. He won't judge."

[caption id="attachment_3885" align="alignleft" width="270"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-10.33.27-PM.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-3885" alt="Screen Shot 2016-01-26 at 10.33.27 PM" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-10.33.27-PM-270x300.png" width="270" height="300" /></a> Photo: imgarcade.co[/caption]

Depression, unfortunately, isn't a choice. No one welcomes it, and it's nearly impossible just to "shake off". If we could make it stop, we would, but we can't.

Picture your beautiful car as <em>depression</em>, and a fresh, icy blanket of snow <em>distorted thinking</em>. No matter how clean and tuned up you may be, you can't stop the snow from falling down. You see the clear road two feet to your left, but you're trapped -- less by the snow than by the <em>belief</em> you're stuck there forever. Your handy tools seem too cumbersome to bother digging out, and as you keep spinning and spinning and spinning your wheels, you loose traction and fuel and drive yourself downright crazy.

But when some well-meaning crackerjack like you (no offense) stands on the clear pavement doing a bellydance yelling, "Is it really that bad?" you're seriously not helping by stating the obvious.

<em>Perspective</em> is the antidote for <em>distorted thinking</em>, so sprinkle that <del>shit</del> salt all over that icy snow. Melt the stuff down, Dude. Reach into the window, crank that wheel a smidge to the left, then remain on standby while <em>depression</em> works its way out. Don't try to rescue or be the hero, even though God knows you deserve a medal. That will come later, after the melt. But if you can't understand this or can't follow these instructions, head to the nearest 7-Eleven, buy the latest issue of Hot Rod, and let the grownups figure life out.

Okay…my tough love rant is now over.

But you can stop beating yourself up. Depression isn't easy for anyone to understand, let alone manage.

I just want to make sure we both agree that, while a label certainly doesn't define the person, "depression" has a way of feeling like it does, thanks to our own cognitive distortions reinforced by frustration from others:

"I'm <em>Depressed</em>."
"Why am I so <em>Depressed</em>?"
"Why can't I stop being <em>Depressed</em>?"
"You're making me <em>Depressed</em>."
"Why am I the only one who's <em>Depressed</em>?"
"I shouldn't be <em>Depressed</em>."
"I should have realized sooner that I was feeling <em>Depressed</em>."

We "should" and "shouldn't" all over ourselves, to the point of believing we deserve to feel this bad…only to hear our negative thoughts echoed by others:

"She's <em>still</em> Depressed?"
"Will she <em>always</em> be Depressed?"
"Does <em>everyone</em> get that angry when they're Depressed?"
"I can't even <em>remember</em> when she wasn't Depressed."
"<em>How long</em> does it usually take for her to stop being Depressed?"
"<em>Are you serious</em>? You're actually Depressed over <em>that</em>?"

Look. It's not your fault you can't always be there for her in the ways that she needs, because so few of us are comfortable talking about this subject. And yet depression is real, and it's difficult -- for you and for her. Sometimes, the best way to coax her out of that rut or that wreckage  is to stand there, even as the gapers gawk, just showing her you're not grooving for the getaway today.

What depression does best is to test one's sense of trust -- in ourselves, in others, and in everything we know -- so it might take some patience before she presses the "unlock" button. She's not trying to be difficult. That's the worst part about depression. She doesn't want to be locked inside. She wants to be out there, vacuuming with your…little hose…but your Happy-Go-Lucky dance, to her, feels like a mockery. Between us, she's jealous as hell that you're pulling a Britney when she's glued to her seat. She wants to join you and breathe the diesel fumes all around us, but she can't. Just not right now. But she will. So for now, put down your little hose and just park yourself there, with your Happy-Go-Lucky-ness. Sooner or later she'll eventually signal she's ready. Just remember:  your Sorento was redesigned to be "<strong>Sleek</strong> and <strong>Strong</strong> And <strong>Adaptive To Your Needs</strong>," but when someone's depressed, they'll be anything but.

Oh, if you could only see how many of us struggle in silence due to stigma, more comfortable projecting our pride than accepting society's labels: <strong>Depressed</strong>; <strong>Overwhelmed</strong>; <strong>Unbalanced</strong>. These labels <em>are not who we are as individuals</em> -- they're just feelings -- and believe it or not, we already know that. But while logic tells us feelings are not always the truth, try explaining that to someone whose wife left him for another, or to the mother whose child has died of cancer, or to the young man who just lost his third job, or to the woman who cannot conceive, or to the man who numbs his pain with alcohol, or to the middle-aged mother who's lost her sense of self. These feelings of sadness and desperation are <em><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>real</strong></span></em>, and they're sneaky little buggers, like Smart Cars in your blind spot.

But I really don't want to trouble you, Mr. HGL, and I've taken up far too much time. I can only imagine how this subject matter's probably blown one of your gaskets. I just had to write to let you know how much I recognized your efforts to cheer your So &amp; So up, and that next time, the best thing you can do, if I may be so bold, is to consider depression for what it is: a journey best navigated through compassionate merging, rather than forcing someone into the fast lane.

