I do.
And it sucks.
And it's forever.
And I've had it with how many people won't talk about this shit.

Eight years ago, when I set out to spend a year writing, I'd been teaching preschool, feeling pretty darn happy with my life. Well, at least as happy as I thought I could be as a preschool teacher surrounded by happy children and engaged parents and colorful pictures and songs and books and GOODNESS.

But something inside was missing. Something I couldn't easily identify, a longing, of sorts, to tell a different story.

I'd already read so many stories to my students -- tales that brought them joy and laughter, about themes that explained the world. Colorful, predictable, surprising, unexpected. Every story was a metaphor for life and how to navigate it. So what story did I need to tell?

Writing experts advise to write what we know, but as I started I thought, "Well, the one thing I know like the back of my hand is what life feels like living with depression."

[insert laughter here]

<em>Nah</em>, I thought. <em>That's the last thing people want to read about. That's too sad. That's too gloomy. That's just way too waah waah waaaaahhhh. That's not fun. That's not uplifting. That's not a book someone would <strong>grab</strong>. </em>

<em></em>Back then, I thought my goal was all about getting published. <em>Forget the idea of a book about depression! You're 40 years old! Write something positive and powerful. Something unique and memorable and worth a second read.</em>

I decided I should tell a story that INSPIRED someone. Something about survival and stability and finding one's anchor when life feels adrift.

[caption id="attachment_3822" align="alignleft" width="215"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-29-at-12.53.17-AM.png"><img class="wp-image-3822 " alt="seanheritage.com" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-29-at-12.53.17-AM.png" width="215" height="225" /></a> seanheritage.com[/caption]

And so, I wrote a children's novel about a girl on a sailboat. A fictional tale. And it was the slowest, hardest, most painful thing I've ever done (except for giving birth, but still, really, really tough).

And for the past 8 years, I've been working and reworking and reworking that novel.

Don't get me wrong. I love that book. And I WILL publish it, even if it's only on a dare or because someone bets me a dollar that I won't go through with it. Just watch me. I'll pull all 40 drafts off my laptop and self publish every one of them just to prove how quickly and easily anyone can publish anything these days...because I really did learn a lot more than just how to write a novel in these past 8 years. The publishing landscape sort of exploded before my eyes...

..But that just wasn't the story I was meant to write. And I've never been more sure of that than I am right now, because I've discovered something along this journey:

You don't decide what to write about. If you're open and willing, your heart tells you what to write, and your fingers just start flying. And that's what's happening right now. I'm sitting at my dining room table in the middle of an ice storm avoiding paying my bills and telling myself it's time to go to bed and BAM. It's time. Not 8 years ago. Not someday. Now. Wo here goes nothing. (I actually meant to write "<strong>So</strong> here goes nothing," but I'm digging the <em>Wo, </em>so the <em>Wo</em> shall stay.)

The story I need to tell is one that no one seems to talk about,
because everyone's assuming no one ever wants to talk about it,
but what they're really all doing is just whispering about it anyway,
so let's ask ourselves why we're whispering about it and make this thing happen.
Seriously.

<em>Wo.</em>

This story of mine is called WHY ARE WE WHISPERING? and it's all about <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>living with</strong></span> and<span style="text-decoration: underline;"> <strong>covering up</strong></span> and <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>rising above</strong></span> <strong>depression</strong>. It isn't a story I've actually written YET, but you'd get to Ride the Waves with me (wink wink) as I create it and share it, word by word, on this blog. I don't know about you, but I'm sensing an adventure. C'mon. Whaddya say?

To be fair, there ARE people out there talking about depression and writing about depression and even shouting about depression. Yet I think the whispers continue because the stories aren't shared in the grocery stores and on the playgrounds and in schools or in homes without judgment. Depression is still perceived as a character flaw and a weakness rather than what it is: a medical condition and a disability.

My story's about not being defined by depression and not being ashamed of it. It's about how I've struggled with it, how I've learned to talk about it and why I think we all need to know about it.

For me, depression is so, SO much more than sadness. It's a trillion times heavier than feeling totally bummed out.

Depression's like wearing a hooded, full-body x-ray blanket from the dentist's office
while trying to drag two tranquilized Saint Bernards
through a thigh-high saltwater river
upstream
into a deluge of a thousand <del>Kristin Wiigs</del>
<del>Amy Schumers</del>
<del>Melissa McCarthys</del>
Fat Amys
all laughing in their inner tubes
with umbrella drinks
and misting fans
in a 105-degree dry heat.

That's what depression feels like. For me. <em>Wo. </em>

[caption id="attachment_3812" align="aligncenter" width="341"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-29-at-12.38.07-AM.png"><img class=" wp-image-3812 " alt="foodiggity.com" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/12/Screen-Shot-2015-12-29-at-12.38.07-AM.png" width="341" height="320" /></a> foodiggity.com[/caption]

You feel like you're the <em>only</em> one.
Like no one's got it as hard as you.
Like everyone else is so happy and adjusted and oblivious to the sadness in the world, while you're the unlucky one who's lucid enough to see how bad things really are but you're just too damn tired to make the announcement. In other words, you're the designated driver and you want to go home instead of having to clean up this fricking mess and chase these assholes down and get them all home safe. It's not fair and you just want to leave, but you know that's not cool and it'll only make things worse. So what you end up doing is chiding yourself for being so negative. You find yourself avoiding everything and everyone, including friends and family and tasks and self-care and work and life.

And it hurts like nothing you've ever experienced and you're convinced it will never, ever feel normal or good or happy or colorful again.

<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Avoidance</span> becomes your closest confidant.
<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Shame</span> is the cigarette you'd sneak out back -- that is, <strong>if</strong> you smoked, but you don't, which is good, because depression kills more people than cigarettes.
<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Weakness</span> is the hammock you just can't wait to curl up into.
And <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Self-Loathing</span> is the only one willing to rock you to and fro. Again, <em>Wo.</em>

So for tonight, that's all I've got. And maybe there isn't a market for this kind of stuff. Maybe I should stick with the children's book and consider myself cured of this wacky quest to share my story.

But maybe there's something to this, and if so, I hope you'll let me know. Right now I have to go to bed, then dig out the car and drive myself to my treatment program.

But, and this is a big but (and really so much bigger than Fat Amy's butt), if I come back tomorrow and see more than 40 likes on this post, I'll know I'm on the right track and that I just might have my work cut out for me.

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/48HqBv5Ropo" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>

Thanks for letting me get this off my chest, and a thousand thanks to Fat Amy for the use of her girth to strengthen my analogy. I needed someone funny AND large, and you were the obvious choice. Apologies to Kristin Wiig, Amy Shumer, and Melissa McCarthy, to whom I suggest eating a sandwich and remaining hilarious.

Sincerely,

Christine
#TBD (touched by depression...get it?)

