        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"How A Middle School Guidance Counselor Changes The World";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:102:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/10/middle-school-guidance-counselor-changes-the-world/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:111:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/10/middle-school-guidance-counselor-changes-the-world/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 01 Oct 2015 00:37:13 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/?p=3692";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7309:"To borrow an analogy from <a href="http://www.school-counselor.org/middle-school-counseling.html">School-Counselor.org</a>, "The middle school counselor is to a middle school as the project manager is to a mid-size software company." I certainly wasn't a middle-school mover-and-shaker, but I had more questions than any one parent, teacher or friend (yup, singular) could handle:

How am I supposed to sit at lunch when all the tables are full?
What do I do when two of my classmates hate each other but always ask me to say who I like best?
How do I tell a teacher I can't understand her handwriting?
Is this my week to be the after-school crossing guard? Where do I pick up my orange vest and the STOP sign?
Why does my P.E. teacher keep calling me the wrong name, then yelling when I don't answer?
Can a 7th grader run for student council?
Am I the only one who spends every other weekend at her dad's house?

It never occurred to me to bother the school social worker, the school psychologist or (God forbid) a busy teacher, because I always had my guidance counselor in my corner.

Sam Hanasz was that person -- the one adult at school I could always approach with any question, big or small, and not feel like a kid.

A group of us met once a week with Mr. H for half of our lunch hour -- just hanging out, talking, and being ourselves. The relationship was organic, relaxed, and comfortable. It provided a sort of anchor during busy weeks of rotating classes and faces and assignments and moods.

If I felt like crying, I knew I could get a pass to see Mr. Hanasz.
If I got a great grade, I'd want to tell Mr. Hanasz.
If my day went to hell, I'd leave a note on Mr. Hanasz's desk.
Walking through the hall, lost in my own thought, Mr. Hanasz would tap my shoulder with a laugh: "Earth to Chrissy."
When my best friend Amy's father died suddenly of a heart attack, my Language Arts teacher relayed a note from Mr. Hanasz the first day after it happened: "I'm so sorry. Stop by if you want to talk."

I didn't learn as much about him as I shared about myself; unfortunately, that's what egocentric middle-schoolers do -- obsess about themselves. But Mr. H made sure we got to know our peer group through ice-breakers and games and good old-fashioned conversation. We talked about how things were going...what our week's highlights (and lowlights) were...who was on our "good" list...and who was driving us bonkers. Our little advisory group gave us opportunities to catch our breath...take note of others...express vulnerable feelings without apprehension. Mr. H modeled empathy and fostered friendships, and only one word describes how he did it all so effortlessly: Magic.

I never appreciated Mr. H as much as I do now, since we live in a school district that eliminated guidance counselors years ago, supposedly due to budget constraints. Although students can make appointments anytime with school psychologists and/or social workers, they miss that essential, supportive, approachable layer of a guidance counselor in their day-to-day lives.

Clearly, my middle-school questions weren't life-threatening, but to my 12 and 13-year-old self-confidence, navigating that social-emotional minefield was a journey fraught with risk of ruining a day, a week, a semester, a reputation, a psyche.

In the 1980's, my guidance counselor lent unconditional support, yet I think today's middle school students need more support than ever.

Imagine being 12, juggling smartphones, Instagram, and Body Mass Index testing. Imagine opening the paper or (more likely) reading a column online about another mass shooting while gulping down a bowl of cereal.

To be sure, there are those who will argue that my generation coddles kids and that we need to let them build their own resolve and self-confidence -- and I couldn't agree more. But these days, when students have questions that might not fit neatly into boxes marked "academics" or "emotional emergencies", to whom do they turn?

For those students fortunate/confident/willing enough to connect with a trusted teacher or administrator, life is certainly good. Other students might reach out to social workers or psychologists with ease -- or at the very least, receive the encouragement of a parent or staff member. But for the students like my younger self -- tiptoeing through the "What if's" and the "I'm just not sure's" -- every question feels like a gamble. A risk. A chance to blow the whole world apart.

And although we've come a long way in our identification and demystification of social-emotional struggles, there's still a stigma -- felt by many middle school kids -- about being seen with the school's social worker/psychologist. And so until educational institutions foster the sense in every student that it's okay to stop by their offices, kids these days often suffer in silence rather than have their peers see them fraternizing with these professionals.

I've worked with enough middle-schoolers to hear the ongoing narrative:

"If I stop by the social worker's office, everyone will think I'm having trouble."
"Only the kids with problems go there."
"It's just not that big of a deal."

Obviously these statements aren't always true, but try telling that to the middle-school student doing anything and everything not to "stand out".

Kids have more to handle than ever before, and they deserve our unconditional support whether they succeed or fail. Their journey is often challenging, so why must we eliminate guidance?

Sam Hanasz, my guidance counselor, was there for me even when I didn't ask him for help. But just knowing I COULD reach out at any time without question made all the difference in the world.

_____________________________________________

