</ul>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Christine Wolf";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17599:"This probably is not the story you expected, but this time around, it's the whole story of an August 5th, 2015 incident at Whole Foods, including accusations of racial profiling and a community in need of Restorative Justice.

After <a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/08/evanstons-whole-foods-owes-ashley-usher-coleman-apology-retraction-after-shoplifting-accusations/">writing about Ashley Usher-Coleman's August 5th experience</a> at a <a href="http://www.wholefoodsmarket.com/stores/greenbayroad">Whole Foods in Evanston, Illinois</a>, I discovered much, much more. This is what I've learned.

<strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Question 1: Can This Ever Heal?
</span></strong>Having participated in the Restorative Justice process, I’ve witnessed firsthand the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">restorative</span> powers gained through 1) rebuilding trust and 2) encouraging healing – for victims, for offenders and for the community.

In America, it's so easy to shame offenders and not deal with what we assume are their excuses. It’s easy to point a finger with rhetorical questions, like:

“<b>How</b> dare you?”
“<b>What</b> were you thinking?”
“<b>Who</b> do you think you are?”
“<b>When</b> did you learn to act this way?”
“<b>Why</b> would you do this when you knew better?”
“<b>Why</b> should I care when <span style="text-decoration: underline;">you</span> caused the problem?”

But really, what do all of those questions have in common?
A dirty little five-letter word: SHAME.

So now, do the hard work, and listen. <b>Really listen</b>. And ask yourself why we don’t do <span style="text-decoration: underline;">that</span> more often.

<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Examining injustice through understanding</span> is the most powerful tool our society has yet to embrace. Can we be an example of how it's done right? Do we truly #StandWithAshley? Or will we shame an offender into isolation?

Our current system of justice is based on a system of retribution and punitive solutions, but my question to you is: "How's that working out for us?"

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Question 2: How Did I Not See This Coming?</strong><strong>
</strong></span><strong>First, I owe Whole Foods -- and readers -- a public apology.</strong>
My column prompted boycotts and insults about Whole Foods by readers who shared the column more than 700 times on social media. I’d fueled the firestorm ignited by Usher-Coleman's claims.

&nbsp;

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/09/Screen-Shot-2015-09-02-at-6.25.33-PM.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3618" alt="Screen Shot 2015-09-02 at 6.25.33 PM" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/09/Screen-Shot-2015-09-02-at-6.25.33-PM.png" width="327" height="60" /></a>

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/09/Screen-Shot-2015-09-02-at-6.25.25-PM.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3619" alt="Screen Shot 2015-09-02 at 6.25.25 PM" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/09/Screen-Shot-2015-09-02-at-6.25.25-PM.png" width="504" height="134" /></a>

Initially, I was relieved by the swift and supportive response. And I felt I’d more than covered my journalistic bases: Despite an online petition circulating and her story forwarded by multiple trusted sources within our community, we’d corresponded directly, numerous times.

Another thing: Whole Foods’ silence only reinforced my belief in her story. Apparently, others agreed.

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/09/Screen-Shot-2015-09-02-at-6.25.05-PM.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3620" alt="Screen Shot 2015-09-02 at 6.25.05 PM" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/files/2015/09/Screen-Shot-2015-09-02-at-6.25.05-PM.png" width="494" height="97" /></a>

Yet it was just after my column went live that significant doubts emerged.

After Usher-Coleman read my column, she messaged me to expand on a fact that she, surprisingly, never mentioned in her 2108-word online description of the event.

<b>“</b>Just to clarify,” she wrote, “the vitamins were accidentally dropped into my large carry all after I removed everything looking for my ChapStick. When I was putting everything [back] in, I inadvertently stuck those in as well. This according to the security guard because I actually have no recollection of doing so.”

<i>Uh…no wonder they suspected retail theft</i>, I thought. <i>Why hadn't she mentioned this earlier? </i>

“How,” I wrote back, “did [security] know they were in there?”

“He said that he started watching me when I picked up a market basket,” she wrote. “So, from the beginning.”

Truth is, I felt guilty for feeling suspicious. I didn’t want to be like the security guard she’d described -- suspecting guilt for no valid reason. She <i>must</i> have been targeted. Right?

<b>“</b>Did anyone else hear him say this to you?” I wrote. “Why would he feel the need to do that?”

No response.

I wrote, “I'll clarify these points in the post right now. Thank you for letting me know.”

But then she wrote:<b> “</b>I cannot remember if it's part of the police report, so [I'd] hold off on that detail for now.”

<b>“</b>Can you snap a pic of the police report and send to me?” I replied. “I can't clarify the details without understanding why [security would have] approached you in the first place. Did he approach you inside the store? When did the guard approach/stop you and how did he alert you to the ‘problem’? Did he give you a chance to pay?”

<b>“</b>After I paid for my groceries,” she wrote. “And no, he did not offer me a chance to pay.”

Shortly thereafter, her Facebook page disappeared. Our dialogue, it seems, was over.

<strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Question 3: Am I Invested In Understanding My Role?
</span></strong>On Friday, August 28<sup>th</sup> as I drafted an update highlighting my questions and concerns, an official from the City of Evanston called, requesting anonymity. After reviewing surveillance video from the August 5<sup>th</sup> incident, the facts, I was told, were indisputable.

“This was retail theft, caught clearly on video,” the source said. “Egregious and intentional.”

It was my turn to go silent. I was totally pissed, mostly with myself.

“Can I see a copy of the surveillance video?” I asked the official. “The last thing I can do is write anything more without verifying. ”

I hung up. I was furious. I thought, <em>Are you flipping kidding me? I believed her. I went to BAT for her. I’d specifically and directly asked her how the bottle ended up in her purse. Had she made it all up?</em>

Then I asked myself: <i>What do <span style="text-decoration: underline;">my</span> actions suggest about <span style="text-decoration: underline;">me</span>? Why hadn’t <span style="text-decoration: underline;">I</span> waited for Whole Foods’ response for a statement? Why hadn’t </i><em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">I</span> somehow confirmed her statement before sharing it on social media? How could <span style="text-decoration: underline;">I</span> be so naïve?</em>

The video had already been turned over to the Evanston Police Department, so all I could do now was what I should have done before I hit publish: Keep bugging someone at Whole Foods for their side of the story.

Not surprisingly, Whole Foods Marketing Director Keith Stewart seemed more than ready to take my call.

“We haven’t made a statement,” he explained, “because it’s our policy not to damage someone’s personal reputation.”

<i>Of course they don’t,</i> I told myself. <i>They leave <b>that</b> dirty work for the untrained, new-media journalists like me, who can write anything we want and hit publish faster than you can say bundle-me-Xfinity.</i>

And though Stewart wouldn’t comment on Whole Foods’ shoplifting policy, he said, “We’re very familiar with the signs of retail theft, like nervous behavior, looking around, intentional concealment. Accidental things happen all the time, but there’s a big difference between that and retail theft.”

Then I blurted out:

“You know, I was working on a post today about my reservations.”
“It struck me as odd when she modified some details after the column gained traction.”
“I’m still processing all of this.”
“I want to make this right.”
“I can’t begin to tell you how hacked off I am right now.”

How, I wondered, did pre-Internet journalists manage to W…A…I…T until they got a statement from someone? Hadn’t I gone the extra mile getting the victim’s statements in writing? But what I’d really done was share half a story – and possibly not even the truth.

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Question 4: What Am I Doing To Help Make Things Right?
</strong></span>“Is it possible to get a copy of the video?” I asked Keith Stewart.

“It’s in the City’s hands now,” Stewart told me. “You’d have to ask them for a copy.”

It was now Friday, August 28<sup>th</sup>, just before 5:00 p.m. Rather than head to the Civic Center and risk arriving too late, I drove straight to the Police Department to fill out a Freedom Of Information Act (<a href="http://www.foia.gov/faq.html#thefoia">FOIA</a>) request.

“Sorry, but no dice,” I was told. I’d have to file the request with the City Clerk on Monday. Figures. Besides, I needed a lesson in patience.

Monday, September 1st really wasn’t a great day to bug Evanston Police Commander Joseph Dugan: He was busy with a homicide investigation following an early morning shooting in the 1800 block of Dodge Avenue. After leaving him a message, I forgot my worries of career suicide and imagined those two young men, shot near our public high school – particularly the one who did not make it. Then I sat in my car and cried.

Later, just before 3:00 p.m., Cmdr. Dugan called. “I’ve got some time now to watch the surveillance video.”

“I’ll be right there,” I said, driving the six blocks instead of walking.

We made small talk walking through several offices, searching for a computer to read the DVD. I realized, in my haste, that I’d forgotten my glasses.

Then, as the video loads, I wonder how and why I am even here.

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Question 5 : Am I Certain I Know The Truth?
</strong></span>I pull out my printout of Usher-Coleman's exact description of her oversight, just so I am clear. Here, again, is what she wrote:

“the vitamins were accidentally dropped into my large carry all after I removed everything looking for my ChapStick. When I was putting everything [back] in, I inadvertently stuck those in as well. This according to the security guard because I actually have no recollection of doing so.”

And here is what I saw on the video, multiple times, alongside Cmdr. Dugan:

She looks around several times. Takes the bottle off the shelf. Takes a small bag out of her larger one. Places the bottle inside the smaller one, secures it shut, and places it into the larger bag.

We watch it again, just to make sure. And we are sure. There is no doubt.

Then, at the checkout, as she unloads items from her basket onto the conveyor belt, she takes a reusable Whole Foods bag from the sales rack and adds it to her pile. As the clerk scans items, she steps away, then returns with what appears to be a loaf of bread. She places it on the belt and removes the unscanned reusable bag, stepping toward the already-scanned pile, holding the unpaid bag just below the counter. She then raises the reusable bag, puts it onto the side of the belt with the scanned items, and loads those items into its opening.

Later, driving with one of my kids, the lyrics of song, played hundreds of times before, sound hauntingly brand-new:

Check your handbook, it's no trick
Take the chapstick, put it on your lips […]
Why would you lie about something dumb like that?
Why would you lie about anything at all?
--From Vampire Weekend's <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aSdwnG5abeg">Oxford Comma</a>

“I really hoped the video proved nothing,” I'd said to Cmdr. Dugan earlier as I left the police station. And I truly did.

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Question 6: Am I Responding To (or With) Actions Or Strategies That Endure?
</strong></span>Regardless of truth or fabrication, however, this story struck such a deep nerve because <b>racial profiling</b> and <b>racial favoritism</b> are so unrelentingly real, so widespread and so absolutely wrong. When we were told about a clear case of it happening in our grocery store over something as benign as oversight? The absurdity unleashed a reaction I can hardly explain. I wanted to shake that security guard and make the racism stop – and – my God! Look! Here, before us were what felt like <b>multiple</b>, <b>tangible</b> ways to <span style="text-decoration: underline;">make</span> it stop, by…

•Making an example of the store on social media.
•Standing with neighbors and boycotting the store.
•Signing and sharing a petition online demanding justice.
•Reaching out to the victim directly, offering support.

Anything, everything seemed entirely possible, right? Those were all the EASY solutions. But did they address the issues of racial profiling and racial favoritism in a lasting way, or were they simply temporary forms of punishment/retribution/shame (towards Whole Foods) and support (for Usher-Coleman)?

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Question 7: What Can Be Learned?
</strong></span>Through all of this, there's an obvious lesson about social media: Regardless of intent, every post has a life of its own. Who'd ever imagine a personal Facebook post dissected and shared in a platform like this? As it happens, we all should. As Usher-Coleman wrote in the comments section of the Patch.com article: "...as for my FB post, it was intended for my friends as a way to feel support. I had no idea that it would become what it has..." and "...I didn't ask for people to start a petition, for people to write news articles, for people to picket." But we all, in fact, did, because of her post.

I think it's a mistake to dismiss Ashley Usher-Coleman entirely. I believe racial profiling has happened to her and to others -- and that it will continue to occur if we don't all address the problem. Did it happen at the Whole Foods in Evanston? I'm not the judge, and my trust is clearly shaken -- but it's worth rebuilding, because we need to move forward, not back.

But the most important lesson, I believe, is maintaining compassion. I don’t know what compels an individual to steal, misrepresent, or omit critical details, but she has her reasons, right or wrong; and until I know the individual’s feelings, I cannot fully understand what motivates the actions.

And while I don’t condone stealing, misrepresentation or omission of critical details, my intent was and is to always help someone (and yet note how THAT intention ended up backfiring). Legalities aside, my heart remains open as I offer compassion, because in the future -- even now -- I can only hope others respond similarly towards me.

Is there an opportunity for our community to #StandWithAshley? To organize a Restorative Justice event to bring Whole Foods and the community together with Ashley and make things better? To demonstrate support for Whole Foods? Have we asked ourselves the tough questions:

1. <strong>Can This Ever Heal?</strong>
2. <strong>How Did I Not See This Coming?</strong>
3. <strong>Am I Invested In Understanding My Role?</strong>
4. <strong>What Am I Doing To Help Make Things Right?</strong>
5. <strong>Am I Certain I Know The Truth?</strong>
6. <strong>Am I Responding To (or With) Actions Or Strategies That Endure?</strong>
7. <strong>What Can Be Learned?</strong>

I'll say it again: I'm sorry I didn't dig deeper and get more perspective before I ran <a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/08/evanstons-whole-foods-owes-ashley-usher-coleman-apology-retraction-after-shoplifting-accusations/">my first column</a>, but I'm certain I will in the future. I'll continue to write and continue to learn. And I'll #StandWithAshley, because she -- and we -- are all part of a community.

Christine Wolf has been a <a href="http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/chi-christine-wolf-staff.html">freelance columnist for the Chicago Tribune Media Group's <em>Pioneer Press</em></a> and Patch.com. As a community activist, she creates platforms allowing others to share their voices. She lives in Evanston with her husband, their children and two very vocal dogs.

