Sure, the other stuff's important:

Make sure they get lots of sleep and plenty of protein.
Get to know the teacher, the classmates, the classmates' parents, the school social worker.
Volunteer in the classroom.
Smile at drop off when you say goodbye (even when they're crying).
Arrive on the playground with another smile and a beverage (since drinking fountain lines are just too long).
Expect to hear few details until bedtime, when anxiety about tomorrow summons the worst memories of today.

But while you know these things -- and many others --  what you need personally is a magic salve to soothe the sharp, tiny fissure etched on the surface of your heart, the first, most painful symptom of separation heartbreak.

You will survive, though, even when it gets worse, because it will get better, I promise. I've been there.

This year, I'll have a 7th grader, a sophomore and a senior in high school, but ask me about each of their first days of kindergarten and I'll tell you the specific waves of emotion at each goodbye:

<strong>Shock</strong>: How did time pass so quickly since the day you were born?

<strong>Worry</strong>: Will this teacher protect you?

<strong>Joy</strong>: I actually have time to put life and work back in order!

<strong>Curiosity</strong>: Which of these classmates will become your friends?

<strong>Worry</strong>: Who's most likely to make your life hell...and where is that parent?

<strong>Concern</strong>: Did I send the right supplies?

<strong>Worry</strong>: Were my emergency numbers legible on the form?

<strong>Annoyance</strong>: The bell already rang. Why won't they just take them inside? I see tears forming.

<strong>Worry</strong>: Did I lock the car? My purse is in there. Let's get the line moving, people.

<strong>Insecurity</strong>: That mom's looking dressed for success.

<strong>Relief</strong>: My child is laughing with the other kids.

<strong>Worry</strong>: The line is moving. This is it. He'll look back this way. Can he see me?

<strong>Indecision</strong>: Where should I move? Should I even move? Will he know I've moved?

<strong>Worry</strong>: If he sees me, will it make things worse?

<strong>Wonder</strong>: That little boy's running back to his mom. How's she going to manage this?

<strong>Worry</strong>: What if mine does it, too?

<strong>Emotional</strong> <strong>exhaustion</strong>: Can we just get this over, now?

<strong>Worry</strong>: Where the hell is my compassion? Am I THAT self-absorbed? Did I lock the car?

<strong>Fear</strong>: Are we out of coffee at home?

<strong>Surprise</strong>: Is it raining? Is that a tear on my cheek?

<strong>Worry</strong>: Will he see me crying? Oh God.

<strong>Embarrassment</strong>: It's <em>kindergarten</em>, for Christ's sake. I'll see him in a few hours.

<strong>Worry</strong>: He just looked around wildly. He's scared. He's scared. It's a huge school. He'll be okay, right? They keep an eye on them at every minute, right?

<strong>Determination</strong>: This is going to be okay...as long as someone makes the call and gets the line moving. Seriously, people.

<strong>Worry</strong>: He's not talking to anyone now. All the other kids are chattering away. His heart must be racing like a hummingbird's.

<strong>Obsession</strong>: The tissues are in my purse... and my nose is overflowing. Can I wipe it with the back of my hand and, if so, which of these moms (aside from Ms. Dressed For Success) would do the same thing and not judge?

And then, just like that, he went in. Two years later, so did another. And three years later, yet another. My kids made it through that first day, and the next and the next and the next and the next. And so did I.

And I've often wondered how I kept moving, even when they were with others...out of my sight, my care, my protection. How did I learn to not only walk away that first day but to, eventually, put them out of my mind for chunks of time? Some might say it's healthy... but I know it's really a matter of letting go.

And that's why it's so hard...at first. Because there's nothing you want more than for them to be strong, independent people, but to let that happen, you have to take that first huge, earth-shattering step, and this is it.

Remember, though, that the tiny, sharp fissure on your heart heals over at the end of each day when you're reunited. Your love grows even stronger. Literally, day-by-day. You don't even notice it while it's happening, but just as your child inches up over the summer, it happens.

It's the magic of separation heartbreak, and it's worth the pain, as long as you remember to breathe deep and go long; otherwise scar tissue forms and hardens your heart. You cannot lose sight that these fissures will keep coming and coming and coming now...and you must remain pliant enough to endure them. Those who harden will shatter from rigidity.

<strong>Breathe Deep So Your Heart Remains Pliant</strong>
Time does not stop -- but you CAN:
Stop when you <em>think</em> you understand --and simply listen.
Inhale gratitude whenever possible, and you'll find it's easier to exhale positivity. Take a 10-minute walk, pour a cup of tea, text a friend or a teacher or a neighbor or a family member and just say "thank you for your kindness toward my child".
Sleep on the toughest situations -- allow yourself space and rest to breathe deep, to consider decisions and actions and conclusions -- rather than reacting immediately.

<strong>Go Long -- This Is a Marathon</strong>
It's overwhelming thinking you're only just beginning. "How can I have these crazy emotions when she's only in KINDERGARTEN! I'll be a wreck when she's in middle school!" Every parent feels this way <del>at one point or another</del> multiple times throughout their child's adolescence, so you're in good company. You're going to hit bumps along the way -- you won't know if you've done the right thing, said the right thing, or made the right choice as a parent -- and these moments in question are all part of the process of raising good kids. Figure out what works and hold on, and forgive yourself for your missteps. And just as every child is different, you will be different with every child. We teach our kids to move on after mistakes -- so walk the walk and do the same for yourself.

Pretty heavy advice for parents of 5-year-olds, right?

But take it from someone who was there just a blink ago: breathing deep and going long will get you and your kids through.
You can do this.

P.S. Just don't leave your tissues in the unlocked car.

