        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"Evanston&#039;s Whole Foods Ripe With Accusations Of Racism ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:148:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/08/evanstons-whole-foods-owes-ashley-usher-coleman-apology-retraction-after-shoplifting-accusations/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:157:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/08/evanstons-whole-foods-owes-ashley-usher-coleman-apology-retraction-after-shoplifting-accusations/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 19 Aug 2015 16:21:43 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/?p=3511";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:27034:"Just as a journalist will seek reputable sources to support her work, so too will a grocery store security guard identify individuals posing threats to the business, right? End of story.

Then again, maybe not (and when you're finished reading THIS column, read <a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/riding-the-waves/2015/09/not-the-story-you-expected-whole-foods-racial-profiling-restorative-justice/">THIS FOLLOWUP piece</a> for an update on the situation).

For example, a good journalist would never cite Wikipedia as a source, right? After all, there are countless alternative sources available and, if nothing else, Wikipedia's just...oh what's the word I'm looking for...? Ah! Untrustworthy.

And a good grocery store security guard would never presume anything other than blatant theft -- shoplifting -- when a shopper's oversight happens, <em>particularly</em> if she's black. After all, while countless oversights can happen to anyone while grocery shopping, if nothing else, this is a <em>black</em> woman, and she is, of course...oh what's that damn word again?

But let's assume I'm just a plain old mom from Evanston, Illinois, where a <del>first</del> <del>second</del> third Whole Foods recently opened on Green Bay Road -- one that's involved in a social media explosion over its alleged shoplifting charges against a black female business owner, Ashley Usher-Coleman.
<blockquote>From Wikipedia:
"Shoplifting is typically undertaken by amateurs, and involves concealing an item and leaving the store without paying for it. Other forms of shoplifting include swapping price labels of different items, and eating a store's food without paying for it. Commonly shoplifted items are those with a high value in proportion to their size, such as razor blades and cigarettes. Retailers have reported that 0.6% of their inventory is lost to shoplifting. The term shoplifting and shoplifter has not been defined in Law. The word <b>shrinkage</b> is not a synonym for shoplifting, as it includes merchandise loss by means other than shoplifting."</blockquote>
And, with her permission, here is Ashley Usher-Coleman's description of the incident (from Facebook):
<div data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}">

<strong>RACISM: ATTACK MY SPIRIT, BREAK MY HEART, BUT I WILL NOT BE WHO YOU WILL ME TO BE. I WILL REMAIN...BECAUSE I MUST.</strong>

<strong>My heart is broken. And try as I might I just cannot make this ache go away. I am typically an extremely private person. I don’t overshare on social media. For every one picture you see, there are fifty that you didn’t. My wedding had 18 attendees. And I can count with my fingers the number of people who truly know the depths and pain of my story. I aim to look forward, to continue to grow. And only look back to gain knowledge or to re-break bones that never healed properly. I try to be slow to anger and eager to listen/hear. Everybody has a story, I believe. Everyone has a reason they are the way they are, some deep part of their soul that is being trampled on. So perhaps, that’s why they judge and project. I can handle it, I say to myself, for I have been through far worse. But I think I’m tired. Courage takes strength. And strength, even the strongest kind, has its limits.</strong>

<strong>Every morning, for eleven years I get up, get dressed, grab a cup of coffee, and before I walk out the door I put on my brave face. I dig out my kind heart. I make sure I have my patience and empathy in my purse. I’m going to need it. Maybe even before I get to work, if I stop at the local coffee shop. I’m heading to Chicago’s Northshore. Or some days Chicago’s ritzier neighborhoods. I’m a veteran to these parts. I’m used to being pulled over because it “looked” like I was going to commit a traffic violation. I’m used to the shock on people’s faces when I comment that their street reminds me of the one I grew up on. I’m ready to answer the questions that arise when people find out that I went to private school. Were you bussed there? Did you earn a scholarship? I’m used to the wondering face when neither of those things turns out to be true. And the perplexed look on their faces as they try to register that a black man could be a business owner and indeed afford to send his daughter to private school all her life. That he came from poverty, but refused to go on government assistance when his parents died. As long as he was able, he would not depend on anyone. Even if that meant eating saltines and vienna sausages, he was going to work hard. He was going to be a business owner. "Ahhh...she’s the exception." Except I’m not. My school was 50% black. Most of my black friends have Master’s degrees and a few more have their Doctorate. The town I grew up in is filled with law abiding, educated, family oriented people contributing to society like everyone else. They are a part of their PTA’s. They run for public office. Plant community garden. Save for their children’s college education. Worry about raising kids who will also contribute to society. Most of this country was built on the backs of our ancestors. Most of our parents (and most definitely grandparents) can remember the Jim Crow south just 50 some odd years ago. When they couldn’t eat at most lunch counters. When they walked and walked and walked to make a way for their children, for us, for me. Most of our families bought homes and land that has been passed down through the generations so that no one in the family ever went without shelter. This though, goes over the head of many people I come across in the Chicagoland area. These things, this “ New Civil RIghts Movement” that has “come up” since Trayvon Martin and Michael Brown is baseless. If you encounter prejudice then you must have done something to arouse suspicion and make people see you that way. After all, these are new times. We have a black president…</strong>

<strong>...I call bullshit. Every day I have shown up for work, in a place where most people consider me a domestic (not that there is anything wrong with that.) Many shocked that I attended college. Fighting preconceived notions about why I do what I do. But I love it. I believe what it says in the Bible about how to treat the children. I believe more than anything that the greatest way I can contribute is by caring for the next generation. Of course, I’ve had my criticism from blacks as well, who wonder why I work in a predominantly white neighborhood. Why I take my talents and give them to well off “white” children. I can imagine that to them my days probably look like a chapter of The Help. That’s okay. I get it. But I’m an Early Childhood Professional. I’m a cuddler, a teacher, a boo-boo kisser, a cheerleader, a tutor, a hand to hold when one needs courage, a reminder to always be yourself, a bear hug when “being yourself” got your picked on at school, a high-five when the next day you had the courage to hold your head up high, a trustworthy mother figure for Littles so their mothers can make a living for them. But more than that I’m a contradiction. I’m a living, breathing example that what you learn about me on TV is not what is real. I am a safe place to ask race related questions that they may have never gotten a chance to ask until they are adults. I’m an educator of my culture and theirs since American is American and we all contributed. And while I have had the honor and privilege to work with some phenomenal families, when I go to the store, or the library, or the coffee shop I am subject to the looks, the questions, the security detail around the store. The being judged off hand for my race and not my character.</strong>

<strong>This is the reason for my heartache. Last week I was arrested. A security guard at the new Whole Foods on Green Bay had me arrested because I asked to speak to a lawyer. After purchasing $80 worth of groceries I inadvertently exited the store without one of my vitamins being paid for. It was an accident, of course. The security guard admitted that it appeared to be one and agreed to let me go with a warning. That is, if I agreed to sign a legal document stating that I was a shoplifter. I said, I would need to call my husband. To this he got extremely confused and agitated. He wanted to know why, and inquired “are you a child?” After informing him that I would need to wait for my lawyer to call back before signing any legal documents he rendered me belligerent, uncooperative, and had me arrested. Not for the vitamins but because he didn’t “feel like” waiting for my attorney to call back. (Though the entire process from start to finish was about 10 minutes.) Its absurd as I’m sure people make this mistake all the time. In fact, I know this to be true because I’ve asked. Most were given the opportunity to pay for said item and move on. Or given an ACTUAL warning (and not coerced into signing some paper) and let go. All of them were white. I know, I played the race card. I didn’t want to but I must since this security guard stated to the police that he had been watching me since I walked in the store. Really? Why? There is nothing spectacular about a women shopping for bread and vitamins. Nothing spectacular except my race. And because of this my name, my character, and 11 years of hard work are being dragged through the mud because I had the audacity to ask to confer with my lawyer first instead of allowing him to bully me into stating I was a criminal. I was handcuffed, searched, finger printed, and left in a cell for hours- which caused me to have a significant panic attack. For those that don’t know I have PTSD symptoms resulting from situations in small rooms very much like the one I was locked away in. And now I am being charged with a misdemeanor. I have never so much as been suspended from school. I have been left in charge of people's million dollar homes, cars, and more importantly their children are left in my care while they work or travel. All returned in the condition (and hopefully) better than they were left to me. For eleven years! I started my own business 5 months ago and haven’t had to spend anything on advertising. Just referrals have gotten me to a place where I have had to stop accepting new clients. And just like, on a whim, it can be taken away.</strong>

<strong>Answer me this, what is the point? Why should blacks who played by the rules, work hard, and contribute to society- why should we care? Why shouldn’t we all give up? Why shouldn’t we just forget it and become the people that the media portray us to be. Why are the Black Lives Matter protesters thugs and criminals when the Ted Bundy’s of the world are patriots? ARMED patriots. Why are our teenagers judged (and sentenced) more harshly than their counterparts regardless of the fact that most crimes they commit are the same and mostly minor. Why was my husband shoved and belittled last summer at Wrigley because we had to audacity to attend a Zac Brown Concert. Why have employers loved me on the phone and then turned me away, before even speaking to me, when I showed up for a second interview. "I’m sorry, we don’t have anything for you at this time." Why have I been pulled over for “looking like” I was going to commit a crime. Why have people's neighbors threatened to call the police on me when I was waiting outside for a friend, drinking coffee and reading the New York Times. And why, after eleven years of hard work in the community where I both serve and live am I followed from the moment I walk into a store? And then treated like a common criminal. I’m heartbroken. I feel as though Chicagoland has broken me. A crack here, a crack there. I feel like the girl who keeps loving someone who doesn’t love her. Who keeps “looking on the bright side” when really she should move on. Perhaps I should. I think of the Littles that I cared for this week. Will they remember that I held them until they were asleep. Will they remember that I helped them learn to read. Will they remember that I cheered loudly for them at their recitals, graduations, and music programs. Will they remember the hugs I gave when someone had broken their spirit? Or the way I held them up for hours because gas pains made them cry. Will they remember the laughs, the cries, the lessons, the adventures, the experiences that we had together. Will they remember THAT me when they see my culture portrayed on the television? Will they believe what people tell them about who I am, who we are, or what their spirits tell them? Or will the media and the nay-sayers win? Will the good in us always be judged by the misactions of a few of us. After it all, will they still grow up to follow someone around a store because of their skin color. I know they won’t. Their parents won’t allow it. But someone's children will. Perhaps I should give in and just be bitter. But I know I won’t. I can’t. It’s not who I am. I believe the next generation deserves the care that I have to provide. I believe in the value of who I am. And I love what I do. I will persevere like my ancestors in hopes that the next generation will learn a little bit more tolerance and that my children will have it just a tiny bit easier. But after this, my heart may always be a bit broken. And I will never forget what happened to me just one week ago at 2748 Green Bay Rd.</strong>

<strong>I know better than most that people can hurt. I am not a stranger to heartache. But they tell me also, that people can heal. So whatever God you serve, whatever positive energy you implore, please, remember me. Ask for me. Pray for me.</strong>

</div>
Now, let's assume that the white security guard at Whole Foods wasn't aware of how racial insensitivity and unconscious racism plays out. Let's assume this is his first security job, and that he's never been anywhere near someone the likes of me who grocery shops in a rush...or is distracted...or has wrangled small kids at the checkout...or who thinks about her new teenage driver on the roads in the snow...or suddenly realizes she's forgotten the damn toilet paper. Let's assume he's never been there when the bagger and I both forget to lift up the plastic seat in the cart where the bottle of nail polish...the tube of lipstick...the translucent bottle of bug spray...the pack of batteries...the travel-size container of shampoo...the thin plastic container of basil/thyme/chives/oregano...the bottle of spices...the plastic bag with one jalepeño...the comb...or the greeting card envelope has been overlooked. Let's assume the 12-pack of LaCroix is on the bottom of the cart and somehow slips the attention of the cashier and never gets a PAID sticker applied to its cardboard packaging. Let's assume a three-year-old decides a single-serve sleeve of Oreos seems like the kind of thing Mom would love to find in her diaper bag (she would...but I digress). Let's assume the bottle of dishwasher rinse-aid or the bottle of vitamins slides down and along the child seat support bar, resting in a little nook so perfectly that no one notices it until the newbie security guard stops me and says, "Excuse me... you might not have noticed, but it looks like there's a..." However, I can only surmise that this security guard looked at Ashley Usher-Coleman and assumed, because she is black, that she was...there it is...untrustworthy. Because how else is it that the same kind of thing has happened to me and you and everyone we know, but if you're white, chances are you've never been handcuffed and charged with a misdemeanor for an oversight. Or an honest mistake. Or a flub. Or a mix-up. Or an Oh-My-God-I'm-So-Sorry moment that's corrected on the spot with a logical explanation.

Thing is, I don't know Ashley Usher-Coleman, but when her change.org page kept showing up in my feed, I wanted to know more about what happened, so I sent her a friend request on Facebook, then started asking questions. What happened?

"The vitamins were accidentally dropped into my large carry-all after I removed everything looking for my ChapStick," Ashley writes. "When I was putting everything back in, I inadvertently stuck those in as well. This according to the security guard because I actually have no recollection of doing so."

When did the guard stop you? Were you given a chance to pay?

"After I paid for my groceries," she writes. "And no, he did not offer me a chance to pay."

Ask yourself these questions and answer them as honestly as you can. Then ask the same questions, replacing "her/she" with "my/me/I":
Does the fact the vitamins were found in <strong>her</strong> bag raise more suspicion than if they'd been found in <strong>her</strong> cart? Can we assume the guard (or someone else) watched <strong>her</strong> dump out <strong>her</strong> bag's contents -- assuming <strong>she</strong> intended to steal? Was <strong>she</strong> being watched before <strong>she</strong> dumped out <strong>her</strong> bag?? Did <strong>she</strong> appear suspicious to someone for some reason?

All these questions aside, these three points I know to be true:
<ol>
	<li>I'm a 47-year old woman who's never once been stopped, harassed, or interrogated in a grocery store.</li>
	<li>I've had several moments when a cashier, a bagger, another shopper or even one of my kids has pointed out an overlooked item in my cart, under the cart or even in my diaper bag -- or that I discovered (with embarrassment) later. You can say I'm an airhead (and I am sometimes); you can even call me Winona Ryder-like for my very short stature; you can even call me for dinner anytime you like. But don't ever call me a shoplifter, because it's just not true.</li>
	<li>It's taking way too long to move this society into what feels like a fantastical, magical world called TRUE EQUALITY -- whereby a black woman in my own community can claim #1 above.</li>
</ol>
Still, let's assume the response to Ashley Usher-Coleman's Facebook post <a href="https://www.change.org/p/whole-foods-whole-foods-market-green-bay-road-whole-foods-market-green-bay-road-stop-the-racism?recruiter=46533596&amp;utm_source=share_petition&amp;utm_medium=copylink"> and this Change.org petition</a> will get the conversation rolling, get people thinking, and inspire true change. Let's even assume that I've offered Ashley support by posting my own thoughts about the incident on Facebook when I shared <a href="http://www.mcsweeneys.net/articles/what-level-of-atrocity-must-whole-foods-commit-before-i-stop-shopping-there">Paula Kamen's piece from McSweeny's titled "What Level Of Atrocity Must Whole Foods Commit Before I Stop Shopping There?"</a> along with <a href="http://patch.com/illinois/evanston/evanston-woman-claims-whole-foods-had-her-arrested-because-she-black-0">Tim Moran's Patch.com column about the ongoing Whole Foods incident</a> -- and the caption: "Paula Kamen, here's the answer to your headline's question."

In response, a former high school classmate (female) offered Jeff Ruby's <a href="http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/July-2010/Whole-Foods-Versus-Shoplifters-The-Conundrum">2010 Chicago Magazine column titled: Whole Foods And Shoplifters: The Conundrum</a> and the comment, "I remember this story from years ago. Similar."
An Evanston friend added: "This is interesting: the woman in [The Chicago Magazine piece] walks out [of the store]. The one in Evanston stays, but wants to talk to her husband and a lawyer. Lots of cultural differences and expectations here, on both sides of the conflict."
<span style="color: #ff0000;">But another former classmate (male) added: "A non-White person being held accountable for their actions (which they are not denying doing - just trying to 'explain'), with documented due process in full accordance with the law is not racism. Full stop."</span>
Another Evanston friend replied: "If they are being 'held accountable' in a way that a white person would not have then yes, it is racism. Full stop. And don't be so naive as to suggest that a white mother would have been treated the same." <br data-reactid=".1v.1:5:1:$replies10206442506755747_10206443938311535:0.1:2:$comment10206442506755747_10206444828213782:0.0.$right.0.$left.0.0.1.$body.$comment-body.0.$end:0:$text1:0" /><span style="color: #ff0000;">The male classmate chimed back in: "100% agree with you... however, there is nothing in the article that supports that assertion and the other article posted actually refutes it, as that is the exact same situation - but with a white 'accidental or otherwise' shoplifter..</span>
Someone else (male) added: "The security guard targeted the non-white shopper. Why?"
<span style="color: #ff0000;">Male classmate: "In the [column about the Evanston incident], the shoplifter's lawyer asserts that she was targeted. That is not proof. The [Chicago Magazine article] details the exact same Whole Foods policy being enforced with a white shoplifter."</span>
Someone else (male): "In the Evanston encounter the security officer told police he had targeted "non white" customer...again why? She was then "arrested" because she wanted to talk to husband or Attorney about being requested to sign a document accuser her of being a shoplifter. To me..the targeting of this shopper introduces a racial component barring any other reason such as behavior. The rest is Whole Foods being heavy handed in both instances."
And then this doozy from a fellow writer (male): "Omg! Why are stores being so draconian about this...It's a fucking misdemeanor not a felony. You caught someone shoplifting, inadvertently or otherwise. Make them pay for their goods but don't act like they shot a busload of children for Christ sake."
<div data-reactid=".1v.1:5:1:$replies10206442506755747_10206443938311535:0.1:2:$comment10206442506755747_10206444828213782:0.0.$right.0.$left.0.0.1.$body">All morning after reading these responses, I felt shaky and sick. I wanted to respond, particularly to the male classmate's comments, but I knew I'd only be screaming at a self-righteous wall. I even wrote a response and never sent it, proud not to have engaged in an irrational dialogue, giving the conversation (and my frustration) time to settle before hitting send. <strong></strong></div>
But <span style="color: #ff0000;">then, that former male classmate sent me a private message that reads, "C - you may find this interesting...I did", with a link to <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/john-metta/i-racist_b_7770652.html"><span style="color: #ff0000;">John Metta's "I, Racist",</span></a> a piece I'd already read</span> (and admired) when it first came out in June. And suddenly I was reminded how essential it is to stand up to this lunacy, no matter how often it appears or how insurmountable it seems. I'd been waiting to calm down...waiting to get more feedback from black friends, from experts on race relations, from different angles. But what I realized is, I can't wait for all of that support, nor do I need to. <strong>I can only share what I see as a simple truth: What happened to Ashley Usher-Coleman was racial discrimination.</strong> So here, without using his name, is my response to that male classmate for everyone to see:

<em>The blanket statements you made from the start of this thread immediately raised my dander. You "hate" Whole Foods for their "completely" fake claims? You "completely" agree with their response to actions you unequivocally declare to be theft ("the woman stole")? The shopper later described on Facebook that she didn't realize the vitamins were in her cart until she was walking out and the guard noticed them. Believe it or not, this happens to people and it is NOT stealing. It's called oversight, and it's happened countless times to me. Something slips down through the child-seat or under the plastic flip-up seat... things are easy to miss and are often pointed out by the person bagging the items or while unloading my groceries into a car. When's the last time you were shopping and this happened to you? It's embarrassing, but it's human, and it's not stealing when it's an oversight and the action is corrected. If this has never happened to you, be grateful; and if this ever happens to someone you love, ask if they were given an opportunity to correct an oversight that most white citizens automatically receive, rather than a blanket presumption of guilt. Innocent until proven guilty? What this woman wasn't afforded -- apparently due to her being black -- was an opportunity to correct her oversight. She was immediately accused of stealing and treated as such. With everything going on in this country -- rampant and unfair rushes to judgement, frequently based upon color -- it's no wonder this woman's defenses went up when she was asked to sign a paper admitting she'd shoplifted. I respectfully ask you to consider all sides of a situation -- including unconscious racism -- before making blanket statements and rushing to judgement. Otherwise, a) you're digging yourself deeper than you already are and b) if you're lucky, the store you hate (yet agree with [on this issue]) might have a vacant security guard position available.</em>

The nuance of racism, it seems, is so difficult for some of us to see that, unless it's pointed out to us, often repeatedly, it will continue. Have I offended someone in the writing of this piece? Regrettably, chances are that I have in some way, yet I'm willing to listen and keep moving toward racial equality. One thing I will not do is whisper -- and it seems neither does Ashley Usher-Coleman, thank God.).

Assuming we all make mistakes and we all want equality, Whole Foods has an opportunity to make things right by apologizing to Ashley Usher-Coleman, dropping the charges and, if nothing else, reprimanding the security guard. Short of that, the world will just go on as usual, with journalists citing Wikipedia, security guards singling out individuals based on race, and racial equality remaining just a fantastical, magical dream.

Christine Wolf is a <a href="http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/chi-christine-wolf-staff.html">freelance columnist for the Chicago Tribune Media Group's <em>Pioneer Press</em></a>. As a community activist, Christine creates platforms allowing others to share their voices. She lives in the Chicago area with her husband, their three children and two very vocal dogs.

