Oh, now that's rich! Seriously?

Thank God he gave me a day or two to think about it, because at this point, nothing's jumping to mind.

Of course, had he asked for what I totally suck at, I could have offered an earful. My brain floods daily with all the things I'm lousy at. The list runs like a news crawler at the bottom of a TV screen, a constant presence I've just learned to live with.

It occurs to me, though, that in order to identify the things I'm actually good at, I must first purge the negative to make room for the positive. And so, using this post as my mental dumping ground, here's a list of 75 things I totally suck at:

1. Making my bed in the morning.

2. Doing dishes.

3. Reading quickly.

4. Hiding my emotions.

5. Laundry.

6. Twitter.

7. Instagram.

8. French braiding my own hair.

9. Making sure the puppy can't counter-surf human food, only to leave a crap circle on the kitchen floor.

10. Writing with brevity.

11. Following a budget.

12. Exercising regularly.

13. Getting my first novel published.

14. Waking up happy and energetic.

15. Maintaining toned and sexy Michelle Obama arms.

16. Being early for appointments.

17. Wrapping presents beautifully.

18. Sending prompt thank you cards.

19. Passing up a plate of nachos.

20. Resisting the constant urge to write about my family.

21. Maintaining a calm presence while driving with teenagers who may or may not belong to me.

22. Anything that involves numbers.

23. Sustaining interest in tasks that are tedious.

24. Sticking to a regular schedule of household maintenance.

25. Making church a priority.

26. Seeing the glass as half full.

27. Carrying on a conversation while music is playing loudly.

28. Finishing things as often as I start them.

29. Spatial relations.

30. Remembering to pay attention to street-cleaning signs in front of my own house.

31. Working in an office.

32. Following posted speed limits.

33. Accepting myself as good enough.

34. Gardening.

35. Ironing.

36. Sewing.

37. Ignoring criticism.

38. Sitting still.

39. Understanding football.

40. Speaking publicly without trembling.

41. Docking a boat.

42. Cooking without turning the kitchen into a disaster zone.

43. Forgetting how horribly my biological father treated me.

44. Waiting for sales instead of buying retail.

45. Brushing the dogs on a regular basis.

46. Stopping to enjoy life more often.

47. Geography.

48. World history.

49. Navigating Excel spreadsheets.

50. Deleting spam from my email inbox.

51. Understanding Google Drive.

52. Playing an instrument beyond the one song I learned on the piano in 7th grade.

53. Tolerating hatred.

54. Being "chill".

55. Living an envy-free existence.

56. Comparing myself to no one.

57. Waking up easily from anesthesia.

58. Singing.

59. Cleaning behind my refrigerator.

60. Stopping myself from interrupting when I think I have a critical point to express.

61. Completing my to-do lists.

62. Thanking my mother and stepfather enough for raising me with unconditional love.

63. Wearing a thong without fidgeting.

64. Remembering all the words to Queen's Bohemian Rhapsody.

65. Clearing out duplicate contacts in my address book.

66. Making photo albums.

67. Relaxing when I entertain.

68. Remembering to feed the meter.

69. Being efficient.

70. Imagining life without my husband and kids.

71. Staying focused on good posture.

72. Typing numbers on a QUERTY keyboard without looking.

73. Shutting out pain.

74. Sticking to a physical therapy routine.

75. Avoiding prepositions at the end of blog headlines.

Sad and pathetic, but at least these things are now off my chest and out in the open. It's a start, right?  And hopefully, all my positive traits and expert qualities have a little more room to breathe and make themselves known.

For what it's worth, it feels like a weight's been lifted off my shoulders. Feeling the urge to unload? Feel free to share in the comments below. What do you totally suck at?

Christine Wolf is a <a href="http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/chi-christine-wolf-staff.html">freelance columnist for the Chicago Tribune Media Group's <em>Pioneer Press</em></a>. As a community activist, Christine creates platforms allowing others to share their voices. She lives in the Chicago area with her husband, their three children and two very vocal dogs.

